[{'action': 'opened', 'author': 'heinezen', 'comment_id': None, 'datetime': '2021-05-18 11:42:43+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': '----
The term "incompatibility" can also be a bit problematic IMO, so we maybe have to choose a more "tame" term in the app and the FAQ.', 'title': 'FAQ - Revise articles about incompatibility warning card', 'type': 'issue'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'heinezen', 'comment_id': 843100163.0, 'datetime': '2021-05-18 11:45:46+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': '@username_2 I assume you would want to write or draft the articles? :)

In any case, we will try to further improve the articles with user feedback.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'MikeMcC399', 'comment_id': 843126192.0, 'datetime': '2021-05-18 12:23:51+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': '@username_0 
Do we know what percentage of users will see the partial incompatible issue or the full incompatibility issue? My guess is that partial incompatibility is very low numbers and full incompatibility almost zero.

At the moment the app is released for minimum API 23 (Android 6 and above) and BLE has been available since Android 4.1. It is not possible to install on a device earlier than Android 6 (neither through the Google Play Store, nor by sideloading). The only report in GitHub so far since the release of 2.2.1 was about an Android 6 device which did not support peripheral mode.

Users who install the app from Google Play Store are prevented from installing on a device with no Bluetooth support or with no Bluetooth Low Energy support, because this is ruled out by the current manifest file.

If the article is spilt, you could try structuring them so that the introduction is less technical (like the text you proposed) then further down the article provide more technical details for those who would like to know. When I added the version number I looked for a quick, simple and non-contentious change, so certainly this can be optimized and better integrated.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'heinezen', 'comment_id': 843179771.0, 'datetime': '2021-05-18 13:38:39+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "@username_1 We don't know the total number of users that are affected, but the numbers are indeed very low. However, they are not low enough to be insignificant because a few older but popular devices did not receive updates to support peripheral mode.

For the FP2, we know that peripheral mode was not supported with [Android 7 as the OS](https://forum.fairphone.com/t/corona-warn-app-von-fdroid-inkompatibel-auf-fp2/71072). They only recently fixed this with their Android 9 update. A Samsung device with Android 7 was also reported to have an incompatibility warning in the Play Store.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'fynngodau', 'comment_id': 843202499.0, 'datetime': '2021-05-18 14:06:25+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': 'Thanks for the info, will add it to CCTG FAQ.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
